u to ammonia on Fe(II) minerals, and yields are much lower and slower than the free-NH3 route. Upstream glyoxylate generation remains the major weakness.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_014\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent nitrate reduction to NH3 explicitly or note that glycine formation is delayed and indirect.\",\n        \"Reflect lower expected yield and slower kinetics for the nitrate-fed branch.\",\n        \"Strengthen or replace the glyoxylate source.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.93,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.94,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the strongest pathway in the network. Ethanolamine to glycine under alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions with Fe/Co/Ni/Cu catalysts is directly supported by Zhang et al. and fits the environmental framing well. The only limitation is that the origin of ethanolamine is not developed inside the network, but as a standalone glycine-forming module it is excellent.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add a plausible upstream route to ethanolamine to improve integration with the rest of the network.\",\n        \"Specify vent-like conditions more precisely: pH ~9.7, 80-160 C, 0.1-8 MPa, anoxic.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n      \"feedback\": \"The direct carbonyl coupling step is well aligned with the