,\n        \"Support the upstream formaldehyde source more rigorously.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.86\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n      \"feedback\": \"HCN hydration to formamide is plausible and literature-consistent, but in this pathway formamide does not clearly improve the route to glycine as represented; it functions more as a side branch than a mechanistic aid. The pathway remains dominated by the same strengths and weaknesses as the canonical Strecker route, especially the questionable HCN generation step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_003\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Clarify whether formamide is a true mechanistic participant or just part of the broader network context.\",\n        \"Improve the HCN source using literature-backed atmospheric or photochemical chemistry.\",\n        \"Avoid presenting this as a distinct glycine route unless formamide feeds back into product formation.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.87,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.76,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.8,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.75,\n      \"feedback\": \"This non-HCN route is attractive because it reduces dependence on cyanide, and the aminomethanol/formaldimine chemistry is literature-mentioned. Still, the key C-C bond-forming step to glycine from formaldimine and formic acid remains less experimentally validated than other routes. As a complementary branch it is useful, but not among the strongest pathways.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Introduce intermediate states such as iminoglycine if consistent with the computational literature.\",\n        \"Differentiate between experimentally demonstrated and speculative steps.\",\n        \"Retain as an auxiliary pathway rather than a core high-confidence route.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is effectively a variant of the direct carbonyl surface route and performs similarly. The glycine-forming step is plausible and literature-aligned via silicate-surface modeling. Confidence is limited mainly by the provenance of CO/formaldehyde and by adaptation of an astrochemical mineral-surface mechanism to terrestrial prebiotic environments.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Avoid redundant duplication with P5 unless the precursor sourcing is genuinely different.\",\n        \"Specify the relevant mineral surface more faithfully to the cited work.\",\n        \"Clarify terrestrial plausibility versus astrochemical origin.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.8\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.8,\n      \"feedback\": \"This integrated route benefits from showing hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical flow and product mobilization, which directly addresses literature concerns about mineral-bound glycine. The core Strecker chemistry is solid. The weakness remains the HCN source and somewhat self-referential formulation of glycine mobilization as a reaction with unchanged output, but conceptually this is a strong systems-level pathway.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_017\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent mobilization as a state change or extraction process more explicitly rather than glycine -> glycine.\",\n        \"Provide a stronger literature-supported HCN formation route.\",\n        \"State that phosphate-assisted desorption is addressing the observed mineral sequestration challenge.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is strong in scope, connectivity, and literature awareness, and it successfully reaches glycine through several independently plausible modules. Its best-supported branches are the hydrothermal ethanolamine route, the glyoxylate reductive amination route, and the direct H2CO + CO + NH3 mineral-surface route. The canonical Strecker branch is also valid once HCN and formaldehyde are available. Topologically, the network is well connected, has multiple hubs, and displays meaningful convergence. Environmental interconnection is good overall, especially in linking hydrothermal carbon feedstocks to surface synthesis and then to biochemical mobilization/polymerization. Major weaknesses are: incomplete adherence to the requested JSON-style reaction detail; likely missing explicit mineral-agent specificatio