 "methylideneazane", "common_name": "formaldimine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3N/c1-2/h1H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H7NO", "iupac_name": "2-aminoethan-1-ol", "common_name": "ethanolamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H7NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-aminoacetyl)amino]acetic acid", "common_name": "glycylglycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-1-3(7)6-2-4(8)9/h1-2,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated CO2 hydrogenation gives adsorbed formyl equivalents that are released as formate.", "reasoning": "Included as a hydrothermal feeder consistent with alkaline vent CO2 reduction on Fe-S minerals, which the system instructions require and which underpins formate/formic acid availability in prebiotic networks; this is consistent with iron-sulfur world chemistry and vent CO2 reduction discussed broadly in Huber & Wachtershauser (1997) and vent mineral chemistry summarized in Barge et al. (2019). It is used here conservatively as a feeder, not as a direct glycine-forming claim."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface protonation of formate to formic acid", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration and acid-base cycling", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool wet-dry cycling; pH fluctuations allow HCOO-/HCOOH interconversion"}, "mechanism": "Acid-base equilibration during concentration cycles enriches the protonated acid form used as a proton shuttle in downstream aminomethanol/formaldimine chemistry.", "reasoning": "Formic acid is explicitly identified in the literature review as a key glycine-related species and proton shuttle in formaldimine-based routes (Xu et al., 2024 review summarized in source [1]/[5]). This step is a conservative environmental transfer/speciation step rather than a novel synthetic claim."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis with clay adsorption", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Hydration of nitrile carbon under photochemical and mineral-assisted conditions yields the amide.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly notes that HCN plus water plus UV can produce formamide and that formamide can feed amino-acid pathways. This reaction is therefore included as a literature-grounded side branch linked to glycine precursor chemistry (review in source [1]/[5])."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Strecker formation of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentration with UV-active TiO2 in surface setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral to mildly acidic pond chemistry; wet-dry concentration of HCN and NH3"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde and ammonia form an imine/methanimine equivalent that is attacked by cyanide to yield aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical Strecker route to glycine precursors and is directly supported by classic prebiotic chemistry literature and the review provided: HCN + NH3 + H2CO gives aminoacetonitrile, which hydrolyzes to glycine (Miller, 1953; Miyakawa et al., 2002; review source [1], [2], [8]). The use of surface minerals here reflects the requested surface environment and concentration context; the core chemistry follows the literature."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal or acidic work-up cycles"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydration proceeds through amide-like intermediates and ultimately carboxylic acid formation, releasing glycine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine is the established terminal step of Strecker synthesis and is explicitly described in the research summary (Miller, 1953; review source [1], [8]). Acidic or heat-driven hydrolysis is noted in the literature report."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reductive amination of glyoxylate with ammonia to glycine on Fe(II)-rich mineral surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "293K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe(II)-rich mineral surface analogue to ferroan brucite/green rust", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline pH about 8-9; anoxic; moderate-temperature vent/subsurface interface"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxylate condenses with NH3 to an imine/imine-like intermediate that is reduced by Fe(II)-bearing mineral surfaces to glycine.", "reasoning": "The key chemistry is strongly supported by Chimiak et al. (2024), who showed glyoxylate plus NH3 gives glycine on ferroan brucite at 20 C and 1 atm under alkaline conditions, and by related Fe(II)-rich mineral systems such as green rust and magnetite/brucite networks discussed in the report ([3], [4], [9], [10], [14]). Because the required hydrothermal mineral list excludes brucite/green rust, magnetite and greigite are used here as Fe-rich vent analogues while preserving the literature-based mechanism; this should be regarded as mineral-class extrapolation constrained by the provided system requirements."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Nitrate reduction to ammonia on Fe-rich mineral surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "293K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe(II)/Fe(0)-rich mineral reduction system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline pH about 8-9; slow conversion over weeks; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated electron transfer reduces nitrate/nitrogen oxyanions to reduced nitrogen, supplying ammonia for subsequent glyoxylate amination.", "reasoning": "The research report emphasizes that in Chimiak et al. (2024) nitrate is not converted directly to glycine but must first be reduced in situ to NH3 on Fe-bearing minerals, with lower and slower yields than the free-NH3 route ([4], [10], [11], [14], [18]). This reaction is included specifically to address that literature nuance and prior feedback."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal ethanolamine conversion to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353-433K", "pressure": "0.1-8 MPa", "catalyst": "Fe/Co/Ni/Cu metal powder catalyst system represented here by Fe-rich vent mineral/catalyst phase", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH about 9.7, anaerobic alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation"}, "mechanism": "Metal-catalyzed oxidation/dehydrogenation of ethanolamine gives aminoacetaldehyde-like intermediates that convert to glycine under alkaline hydrothermal conditions.", "reasoning": "This is directly based on Zhang et al. (2017), who reported rapid and efficient glycine synthesis from ethanolamine at 80-160 C, pH about 9.7, 0.1-8 MPa with Fe/Co/Ni/Cu catalysts in simulated Archean alkaline hydrothermal vents ([6]). The exact catalyst ensemble in the paper is broader than the required mineral list; Fe-rich representation is used to satisfy the schema while preserving the literature conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Direct surface-mediated coupling of formaldehyde, carbon monoxide, and ammonia to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_016", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "150-200K equivalent warming regime on mineral surfaces; terrestrially modeled as cool concentrated surface microenvironment", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "silicate-like mineral surface analogue", "aqueous": "false", "other": "surface-mediated neutral pathway; included as a mineral-surface transfer of the reported forsterite mechanism"}, "mechanism": "Adsorbed H2CO, CO, and NH3 undergo a low-barrier C-C/N-C bond-forming sequence on the mineral surface to yield glycine directly.", "reasoning": "Mates-Torres & Rimola (2026) computationally identified a low-barrier, exergonic direct route from H2CO + CO + NH3 to glycine on forsterite surfaces, while also finding the surface Strecker route kinetically blocked ([7]). This reaction is included because it is one of the clearest non-HCN glycine routes in the supplied literature. The environmental transfer from astrophysical silicate to terrestrial mineral interface remains less experimentally validated, so this path should be viewed as literature-supported but context-translated."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Formaldehyde and ammonia to aminomethanol", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous conditions in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of ammonia to formaldehyde gives the hemiaminal aminomethanol.", "reasoning": "Aminomethanol is explicitly named in the research summary as a pathway intermediate whose dehydration gives formaldimine, and computational work highlights this manifold toward glycine (Xu et al., 2024 review summarized in [1], [5]). This step is included as a literature-derived intermediate-forming process, not as a claim of high standalone yield."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Dehydration of aminomethanol to formaldimine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "dehydrating mineral surface under UV/wet-dry cycling", "aqueous": "false", "other": "evaporation-driven dehydration"}, "mechanism": "Loss of water from aminomethanol generates the reactive imine formaldimine.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature specifically identifies aminomethanol dehydration to formaldimine as a key route in computational glycine chemistry (Xu et al., 2024 review [1], [5]). Prior feedback noted this chemistry should remain clearly distinct from Strecker rather than being miswired into aminoacetonitrile production; it is treated here as its own branch."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Formaldimine and formic acid coupling to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "computationally motivated route; proton-shuttle role for formic acid"}, "mechanism": "Reactive imine chemistry couples a C1 imine with formic-acid-derived carboxyl functionality to reach glycine through iminoglycine-like intermediates.", "reasoning": "This pathway is supported primarily by computational analysis summarized in the supplied report, which identifies formaldimine, aminomethanol, formic acid, and iminoglycine-like intermediates as key species toward glycine (Xu et al., 2024 review [1], [5]). It is less experimentally secure than Strecker, glyoxylate amination, or ethanolamine oxidation, and is therefore included explicitly as a computationally motivated/speculative but literature-derived branch."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical condensation of glycine to glycylglycine", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces; dehydration-driven peptide bond formation"}, "mechanism": "Repeated concentration and dehydration promote peptide bond formation between glycine molecules.", "reasoning": "Included to demonstrate downstream biochemical relevance required by the framework: glycine made in hydrothermal and surface settings feeds into prebiotic peptide chemistry during wet-dry cycling. This is a standard prebiotic condensation extension consistent with clay/mineral interface peptide literature, included here as a network-connecting downstream step."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Formaldehyde and ammonia to methanimine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface photochemical and adsorption assistance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "imine-forming shallow pool chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of formaldehyde with ammonia yields methanimine, an early Strecker/imino intermediate.", "reasoning": "The literature report notes that in Strecker chemistry HCN and NH3 first form imine-like species and that methanimine/formaldimine are crucial C1 intermediates in glycine-related chemistry (review source [1], [5]). This step is included to make the imine hub explicit without inventing new chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Methanimine cyanation to aminoacetonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted cyanide addition", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated HCN/NH3/formaldehyde surface microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide addition to the imine carbon of methanimine gives aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "This decomposes the canonical Strecker route into explicit imine formation and cyanide capture, matching the literature description that imine formation precedes cyanide attack to yield aminonitrile (review source [1], [8]). It also avoids the prior error of forcing aminomethanol into the aminoacetonitrile branch."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Strecker direct sequence", "description": "Surface Strecker synthesis from formaldehyde, ammoni